Dialysis therapies in older patients with end-stage renal disease.

Malavade T(1), Sokwala A, Jassal SV.

Author information:
(1)Division of Nephrology, Department of Medicine, University of Toronto, 
University Health Network, 200 Elizabeth Street, 8N857, Toronto, Ontario M5G 
2K8, Canada.

Each year a large number of older individuals with advanced renal disease are 
started on chronic dialysis therapy. Life expectancy is estimated at between 2 
and 4 years depending on age, comorbidity, and intensity of medical care 
required in the weeks around the dialysis start time. Survivors remain at high 
risk of ongoing morbidity. Regarding quality of life, many older patients 
express regret over having opted for chronic dialysis therapy and subsequently 
choose to withdraw from treatment, whereas many others maintain a quality of 
life similar to that of age-matched peers. Early assessment and ongoing 
comprehensive geriatric assessment is recommended.

