531. J Craniofac Surg. 2013 Jul;24(4):1314-6. doi: 10.1097/SCS.0b013e3182953a39.

The use of an acellular dermal matrix "sandwich" for the successful treatment of 
a persistent cranial cerebrospinal fluid fistula.

Mericli AF(1), Gampper TJ.

Author information:
(1)Department of Plastic Surgery, University of Virginia Health System, 
Charlottesville, VA 22908, USA.

Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) fistulae are problematic because of the high risk of 
meningitis and other infectious complications, as well as the potential for 
critically delaying chemotherapy in cases associated with malignancy. The 
plastic surgical literature suggests vascularized autologous tissue for the 
treatment of chronically draining CSF fistulae. Many of these patients, however, 
are debilitated, have multiple comorbidities, and may have a limited life 
expectancy, making the lengthy surgery and the associated donor-site morbidity 
of a regional or free tissue transfer procedure unattractive. There is a need 
for an alternative procedure that is a less morbid, yet equally effective 
solution for the obliteration of CSF fistulae. Herein we report the first use of 
acellular dermal matrix to successfully seal a persistent cranial CSF fistula.

